{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654149"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:50:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18603"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18603"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.2,0.72,0.08,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11335"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80411"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11335"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4908"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8093"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8539"},{"type":"tags","id":"8542"},{"type":"tags","id":"9974"},{"type":"tags","id":"9985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9986"},{"type":"tags","id":"9987"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26306"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80411"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe immune system must maintain tolerance to self-antigens while remaining capable of mounting responses against pathogens. This self-tolerance is maintained through both central and peripheral mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism of peripheral tolerance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Negative selection of B cells in bone marrow","Deletion of self-reactive T cells in thymic medulla","Active suppression of autoreactive T cells by regulatory T cells","Presentation of self-antigens by thymic epithelial cells","Expression of autoimmune regulator gene"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive suppression of autoreactive T cells by regulatory T cells\u003C/strong\u003E is a key mechanism of peripheral tolerance. Regulatory T cells (T regs) produce immunosuppressive cytokines and directly inhibit effector T cells that recognise self-antigens in peripheral tissues.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletion of self-reactive T cells in thymic medulla\u003C/strong\u003E - This is central, not peripheral tolerance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpression of autoimmune regulator gene\u003C/strong\u003E - AIRE gene functions in central tolerance within the thymus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegative selection of B cells in bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents central B cell tolerance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPresentation of self-antigens by thymic epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This process occurs during central tolerance in the thymus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanisms of peripheral tolerance include anergy (functional inactivation of self-reactive T cells) and deletion of autoreactive lymphocytes in peripheral tissues.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral tolerance prevents autoimmune responses through mechanisms including anergy, deletion and regulatory T cells.","Regulatory T cells actively suppress immune responses against self-antigens in peripheral tissues.","Anergy occurs when T cells encounter self-antigens without proper costimulation, leading to functional inactivation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18603"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T16:41:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T16:42:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11335"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80411"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"hea